impactiii 2024-11-21 07:01 p.m.
COUNT TWO - 1 M.S.C. § 1302 - FELONY MISCONDUCT
"On or about the 29h of October, 2024, the undersigned DEFENDANT, occurring within the County of Clark, and in the area surrounding of Mayflower National Guard Base, Fort Standish, immorally acted in his capacity as a member of the Mayflower National Guard, betraying his duty to uphold the Constitution of the State of Mayflower and the laws thereof through his blatant violation of several Mayflower State Criminal Codes; particularly resulting in the death of the VICTIM, deriving from the locality of Clark County. See Exhibit A."

Count Two does not descend to the particulars of what actual abuse he committed "as defined by law." It does not descend to the particulars at all. See Defendant's Mot. to Dismiss for Unconstitutional Vagueness (State v. nexvuz, No. CR-0007-24):
Here, Count One fails to inform the defendant of the specific nature of the charges against him, despite the numerous state laws that define the scope of a peace officer's duties. See 4 M.S.C. 5 §§ 1301-1309. Mr. nexuvz is left uncertain about whether he is defending against allegations of unlawful detention (4 M.S.C. 5 § 1305), neglecting the health and safety of a person in custody (4 M.S.C. 5 § 1306), or engaging in unlawful use of force (4 M.S.C. 5 § 1307, et seq.). Without clear articulation of what actions constituted the alleged misconduct, he cannot ascertain what legal violation he purportedly committed "as defined by law."

That motion was granted, and on those grounds, by this Honorable Judge @acerxtro. To allege felony misconduct, State must identify some specific statutory violation that is "defined by law."

We don't have a valid charge on that count at least of which we have identified so far, so we can't really proceed under those grounds—dismissal of all felony misconduct counts therefore will be necessary. Again, see your ruling:
The court observes the fact that the Sixth Amendment's Notice Clause should guarantee notice to be given to all parties automatically, not only when they request it. "A defendant shouldn’t be telling the State to inform him." Defense Attorney sadoimpacto. It is also obviously not intended for the defense to approach the prosecution in a manner such as, "Hey, Prosecutors, you guys forgot to include this element.. can you please add it?" The Sixth Amendment establishes the right to be informed of the nature and cause of accusations, which includes the obligation to delineate all essential elements of the offenses clearly. As the Supreme Court previously held, this notice is a constitutional right that must be adhered to in all criminal proceedings. See Cole v. Arkansas, 333 U.S. 196, 201 (1948) ("notice of the specific charge . . . [is] among the constitutional rights of every accused in a criminal proceeding in all courts.")

As a result, the court will dismiss both counts one and two, subsequently dismissing the case without prejudice and allowing it to be filed again at a later date.

Thank you.
